{
  "text": "For a tight fiber (s = 5) the situation changes. There exists a limiting value of τ (i.e. a certain ω min ), below which no evanescent modes arise. This is clearly visi- ble on the second plot of Fig. 4 , where the first dotted line starts at certain ξ > 0. This effect is similar to the existence of low frequency cutoff in cylindrical waveguide [CITATION_1] . Its emergence depends only on the value of s or, in other words, on the surface curvature. For a large and thin cylinder this effect is negligible. In Fig. 5 the dependence of ω min (R) is drawn. The threshold for the wave propagation is raised with the increasing value of the curvature. In turn, for large R, ω min gradually decreases to zero, which is the value appropriate for the slab. It should be pointed out that for the 2D surface mode no such threshold (for this mode) arises and ω min is permanently equal to 0.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "121757514"
